<HEADLINE>
FT  26 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Capital Industries disappoints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Capital Industries fell 15p to 154p yesterday after the specialist
packaging and financial services group announced a smaller than expected
increase in profits from Pounds 2.45m to Pounds 4.5m pre-tax in 1993.
Mr Peter Underhill, chief executive, blamed the share price fall on the
group's failure to meet profit forecasts of Pounds 5.4m.
'We made a profit but nothing like what we expected,' he said yesterday.
Profits were held back by manufacturing problems at Samuel Jones, the
group's laminated packaging business where anticipated production
improvements did not materialise despite a Pounds 500,000 investment in new
machinery.
Mr Underhill admitted second-half profits had been hit but said the
subsidiary, acquired in late 1992, had increased group turnover to Pounds
74.8m (Pounds 24.3m).
Output had improved in recent months, he added.
A full year's contribution from Samuel Jones also lifted the industrial
division's operating profits to Pounds 3.84m (Pounds 2.2m)
Group operating profits of Pounds 5.3m (Pounds 3m) were further boosted by
Pounds 1.44m (Pounds 1m) from the financial services division - dominated by
its Capital Ventures subsidiary.
Profits generated by the company - which manages Pounds 320m for enterprise
zones - is expected to offset funds lost by the end of the Business
Expansion Scheme, a main source of profits in the past.
Earnings rose to 12.9p (9.8p) and the final dividend is held at 2.4p for a
total of 4.4p (4p).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Capital Industries.
</CO>
<XX>
