<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / International Company News: Loral heads Dollars 1.8bn
satellite consortium
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Loral, the US defence electronics and aerospace group, said yesterday it had
assembled a group of 'strategic partners' and secondary investors who would
provide initial financing for its Dollars 1.8bn satellite communications
system known as Globalstar.
The group, which includes leading US and European telecommunications
operators and manufacturers, is to invest Dollars 275m to begin the
construction and launch of 48 satellites providing voice and data
communications services to at least 33 countries.
The announcement comes at a time of heightened activity by high-technology
companies seeking to secure their positions in the market for wireless
communications. Earlier this week McCaw, the US cellular operator bought
last year by AT&amp;T, and Microsoft, the California-based software concern,
disclosed plans to set up a Dollars 9bn system of 840 communications
satellites.
Globalstar is expected to begin full operations in 1999. Initially the
partners would provide services in 33 countries. Later, local telecom
providers are to be granted licences to extend Globalstar's reach to other
regions.
Loral, which will design and build the satellites and control centre,
projected a customer base of 2.7m and revenues of Dollars 1.6bn within three
years of the system's launch. By the year 2012, subscribers were expected to
total 16m.
Globalstar would offer 'substantially' lower rates than other
satellite-based systems, according to the lead contractor, and its cost to
customers would be only a little higher than that offered by cellular
providers.
The European investors in Globalstar are Alcatel, the French communications
systems supplier, and Vodafone, the UK's largest cellular operator.
Alcatel, a leading supplier to the international mobile communications
market, is responsible for design and delivery of payload modules to be
mounted on the satellites. Vodafone, which is investing Dollars 37.5m, will
use the system to offer subscribers using special handsets a global roaming
capacity and a service in remote regions of countries - such as Australia
and South Africa - in which it is building terrestrial networks.
Loral said the key to Globalstar's cost competitiveness was its use of an
advanced digital transmission technology, developed by Qualcomm, a
California high-technology supplier. The system is compatible with existing
wireless communications systems.
</TEXT>
