<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / International Company News: GE Capital contests board slots
at Kemper
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GE Capital yesterday put forward four of its own nominees for election to
the board of Kemper, the Chicago-based financial services group. The move
signals the outbreak of open hostilities in its Dollars 2.2bn struggle for
the group.
If elected, the four nominees - all former executives of either GE Capital
or its parent, General Electric - will push for the sale of Kemper for at
least the Dollars 55 a share being offered by GE Capital, the company said.
Kemper's board last week voted unanimously to reject GE Capital's offer,
which had been made to the company's directors. GE Capital's response
yesterday marks the outbreak of the first full-scale proxy solicitation
battle in the US for several years.
In a proxy battle, one or more shareholders seeks to impose their will on a
company's board by gathering support from other shareholders. GE Capital
said yesterday it held 100 shares in Kemper.
The GE financial services subsidiary said it would write to Kemper
shareholders in the next 10 days to put its case for a sale of the company.
Its four nominee directors will come up for election at the Kemper annual
general meeting, on May 11.
The nominees will contest the four board seats up for re-election at the
meeting, among them that of Mr David Mathis, the Kemper chairman.
</TEXT>
