<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / International Company News: Northrop to shed 3,000 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Northrop, the US defence company which is engaged in a Dollars 2bn battle
for control of Grumman, plans to cut 3,000 jobs this year, or 10 per cent of
the total.
The cuts mark the latest in a series of steps to shrink the company to cope
with falling US defence spending. Its workforce has fallen to 30,000 from
more than 48,000 in early 1988.
Northrop's cost-cutting has been driven by declining sales. It expects total
sales this year of Dollars 4.4bn, compared with Dollars 5.1bn in 1993 and
Dollars 5.6bn in 1992.
The company's main product is the B-2 bomber, which employs 11,400 staff.
Around 1,300 people will go from this division, with roughly the same amount
from the separate aviation division, which employs 9,300. The remaining
losses will be in electronics.
Northrop is itself widely seen as a potential takeover target, following its
emergence as a bidder for Grumman in competition with Martin Marietta.
Grumman, which agreed earlier this month to a Dollars 55-a-share merger with
Martin Marietta, said yesterday that its board had decided to start talks
with Northrop, which has launched a rival bid for Grumman worth Dollars 60 a
share.
</TEXT>
