<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Strong second half helps lift CIA to Pounds
4.3m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CIA Group, the UK's largest independent media buyer, announced pre-tax
profits up by 17 per cent from Pounds 3.65m to Pounds 4.28m for the year to
December 31 1993, following a strong upturn in business during the second
half.
The group is recommending a 2-for-1 scrip issue 'in order to improve share
marketability'. CIA's share price has increased about fivefold since it came
to the market in 1989.
Yesterday the shares closed unchanged at 390p.
Turnover increased by 21 per cent from Pounds 235m to Pounds 285m, although
new business gains were down from Pounds 76m to Pounds 69m. The group said
there had been strong growth of business from existing clients and client
losses were lower than for many years.
Mr Chris Ingram, chairman and chief executive, said he expected growth of
between 5 and 6 per cent in clients' media budgets in 1994.
This year would see faltering recovery in the UK and continuing recession in
mainland Europe, he said.
The group expects to continue building its European network and increasing
the number of joint ventures during the year.
The fall in interest rates meant a drop in investment income - down from
Pounds 1.5m to Pounds 916,000.
Earnings per share increased by 18 per cent from 15.72p to 18.54p.
A proposed final dividend of 3.68p makes a total of 5.14p, also up 18 per
cent.
</TEXT>
