<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Stronger dollar helps Reckitt rise to
Pounds 260m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sharp rise in the dollar helped Reckitt &amp; Colman, the consumer goods
group, to increase pre-tax profits from Pounds 165m to Pounds 260m on an FRS
4 basis. The 17 per cent appre-ciation in the dollar against the pound, and
other exchange rate moves, added some Pounds 16m to Pounds 17m to pre-tax
profits.
Excluding the Pounds 19m coupon on the group's Pounds 200m of convertible
capital bonds, profits rose 51.4 per cent to Pounds 279m up from Pounds
184m, restated for the Indian activities' move from associate to subsidiary
status.
A proposed final dividend of 11.1p (10.25p) gives a total of 17.55p (16.2p)
a rise of 8.3 per cent. Mr Vernon Sankey, chief executive, said the dividend
increase reflected Reckitt's policy of progressive increases above the rate
of inflation.
Group sales rose 8.4 per cent to Pounds 2.1bn, and operating profits were up
from Pounds 275m to Pounds 315m. Interest charges, excluding the bond
coupon, rose from Pounds 33.7m to Pounds 35.6m as sterling deposits fell and
attracted lower returns. Strong cash flow cut net debt by Pounds 97m to
Pounds 216.5m, excluding the capital bonds, compared with shareholders'
funds of Pounds 704m (Pounds 618m).
Mr Sankey said that one objective in 1993 had been to increase the
proportion of profits from North America, which includes Mexico, and this
had gone up from 16 per cent to 21 per cent. Another was to raise the
proportion from faster growing economies such as South America and South
East Asia, and these had risen from 16 per cent to 20 per cent in spite of
hyper-inflation in Brazil.
Operating profits from household and toiletry rose from Pounds 188m to
Pounds 206m, helped by new product development. Pharmaceutical profits rose
from Pounds 42m to Pounds 45.5m, with extensions of products such as Dettol
and Lemsip. Food profits were up from Pounds 45m to Pounds 54.3m, in spite
of the effect of a soft drinks price war on Robinsons and poor summer
weather.
Stated earnings per share were 45.02p (25.16p), but the underlying earnings
growth was 10.1 per cent to 43.64p (39.62p).
COMMENT
Although the shares fell 10 1/2 p to 605p yesterday, this probably had more
to do with the market than any real disappointment with the numbers.
Reckitt's merits lie in its strong cash generation, high margins, strong
brand positions and geographical spread, all of which contribute to the
regular progression in dividends. However, unlike its mustard, Reckitt never
lights the fire of the mass of investors. Hence a low prospective p/e, of
around 12 1/2 on pre-tax forecasts of Pounds 310m-plus, and a historic yield
of 3.6 per cent which should continue rising faster than inflation. For
investors seeking reliability rather than fireworks, Reckitt is a good bet.
</TEXT>
