<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Sun Alliance returns to black - Pounds 350m
turnround achieved by emphasis on sound underwriting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sun Alliance, one of the UK's largest insurers, returned to profit in 1993,
after three consecutive years of losses, with Pounds 221.7m pre-tax, against
losses of Pounds 129.6m.
The group said the turnround was achieved by an emphasis on sound
underwriting and generating sufficient profits on the general insurance
business to absorb continuing losses on its domestic mortgage indemnity
business.
The year also saw a strengthening of the balance sheet, with shareholders
funds rising by Pounds 465m to Pounds 2.01bn and solvency - net assets as a
percentage of non-life premium income - returning to 64 per cent, compared
with the 54 per cent of last year.
Earnings per share were 22.3p, against losses of 16.1p and the board is
recommending a final dividend of 9.5p, for a total of 14.75p (14.25p). The
shares closed the day 12p up at 326p.
Premium income from general insurance in Sun Alliance UK fell slightly to
Pounds 996m (Pounds 1.01bn), but was accompanied by a return to underwriting
profit of Pounds 3m against losses of Pounds 190m.
General insurance business in Sun Alliance International generated premium
income of Pounds 859m, up from Pounds 825. Losses on underwriting were lower
at Pounds 136m (Pounds 248m).
Though underwriting of the general business in Sun Alliance Overseas once
again made a loss of Pounds 110m, premium income was up sharply, to Pounds
1.54bn (Pounds 1.3bn). The life side premium income rose to Pounds 394m
(Pounds 260m).
This increase came partly from the acquisition of Hafnia in Denmark during
the year.
On the life side Sun Alliance suffered a drop in its premium income in the
UK to Pounds 740m (Pounds 1.04bn) as a result of a fall in its single
premium business, although its annual premium income rose.
The group said that it had been prepared to sacrifice some market share
rather than write business at a loss.
Mr Roger Taylor, who will be group chief executive from July, warned that
the favourable recent period of mild weather would not last, and said that
in many classes of insurance premium rates were too low for the risks being
underwritten.
Sun Alliance is not making any special provision for potential compensation
to be paid to any of its 18,000 clients who had transferred out of
occupational pension schemes.
See Lex
</TEXT>
