<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Laing chairman hits out at banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Banks and institutional shareholders which have supported 'enfeebled
contractors' have added to damaging over-capacity in the UK construction
industry, Mr Martin Laing, chairman of John Laing, said yesterday.
His remarks, which accompanied the the construction group's annual results
for 1993, were made as rival contractor Mowlem launched a Pounds 63.1m
rights issue to refinance the group.
Laing, which announced a 57 per cent rise in 1993 pre-tax profits to Pounds
18.3m, has previously complained that the efforts of banks and shareholders
to prop up ailing companies has left too many contractors chasing too few
orders in the recession.
Mr Laing said that highly borrowed contractors needing a regular flow of
cash payments to meet interest charges were desperate to win work 'at the
expense of profit'. He estimated that there was up to 30 per cent
over-capacity among UK contractors.
The comments run contrary to traditional criticisms that banks are too quick
to call in receivers. Mr Laing stressed he was not aiming his comments at
any particular contractor.
In response to low UK profit margins, Laing was seeking more work overseas.
It was also increasing its involvement in privately financed infrastructure
projects where these provided satisfactory returns. Laing was prepared to
take small equity stakes in these developments if required.
</TEXT>
