<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Optimism lifts P&amp;O shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The share price of The Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company rose
27p to 695p yesterday, as the shipping, transport and property group
revealed a recovery in earnings, and an optimistic outlook. Pre-tax profit
was Pounds 523.7m, against Pounds 270.4m, boosted by Pounds 278.5m profits
from investment sales.
Lord Sterling, chairman, said the businesses had performed well across the
board since the start of the year. 'For the first time, it may be that we
will find ourselves firing on all cylinders at the same time.'
Turnover rose 4 per cent to Pounds 5.75bn, but excluding discontinued
operations, such as the sale of Sutcliffe Catering, the figure increased 12
per cent to Pounds 5.59bn. Operating profit after interest, but before a
Pounds 15m provision, rose 25 per cent to Pounds 260.2m, outlining the
improvement in underlying businesses.
Bovis Homes, the UK housebuilder, rebounded into a Pounds 8.2m profit, from
a Pounds 26.6m loss, because of a 46 per cent increase in unit sales. Bovis
Construction Group also returned to profitability with a Pounds 10.3m
contribution, and its worldwide order book rose 32 per cent to Pounds 4.5bn.
Investment properties contributed Pounds 104.9m (Pounds 90.9m), but the
development business lost Pounds 17.6m from write-downs.
P&amp;O announced a Pounds 15m provision for restructuring its ferries business
before the Channel tunnel opening. However, the cruise and ferries
operations saw profits rise 10 per cent to Pounds 168.5m.
The container division increased profits marginally, because of rising cargo
volumes and stable costs, but bulk shipping continued to suffer from
recession. The combined division fell slightly to Pounds 31.1m.
P&amp;O Australia had a record year with a 20 per cent increase in profits to
Pounds 30.4m, helping to push the contribution from Asia Pacific to 17 per
cent of group sales.
Gearing has been cut from 84 per cent to 53 per cent, due to asset sales,
and the company is close to covering interest costs - Pounds 125m (Pounds
130m) in 1993 - with investment property income.
The dividend is maintained at 30.5p, with a final dividend of 6.5p. This was
not quite covered by recurrent net profits, and analysts do not expect an
increase in 1994. Earnings per share were 68.5p (32.3p).
Ferries, Page 26
