<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Clinton to release more tax returns on Whitewater
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton said last night it appeared he had lost less money on
the Whitewater land investment in Arkansas than he had previously stated. He
promised to release today tax returns dating back to the 1970s which would
reveal to the public that he was concealing nothing.
In relaxed mood at a nationally televised press conference dominated by
Whitewater questions, Mr Clinton insisted that 'the American people should
know that I and my administration will not be distracted'.
Wryly noting media fascination with Whitewater, he said he was surprised
that his poll ratings had not fallen by more than they have. He reiterated
that nothing would be withheld from the independent counsel, Mr Robert
Fiske.
Mr Clinton ducked no questions. He maintained his administration had higher
ethical standards than its predecessors and said that, if mistakes had been
made, 'we learn as we go along'.
His specific confession was that he had simply forgotten that, in 1981, he
had raised a short-term personal loan from Mr James MacDougal, his
Whitewater partner and formerly chief of an Arkansas savings and loan firm,
to help his late mother buy a house in Arkansas.
Mr MacDougal has said in interviews he remembers making a personal loan to
Mr Clinton. The president said he had racked his brains to remember this and
it had only come back to his mind when he was proofreading the unpublished
memoirs of his mother, Mrs Virginia Kelley, who died in January.
He calculated this meant that his total Whitewater losses, previously stated
to be about Dollars 69,000, should be reduced by a further Dollars 22,500.
Should he be found liable to any additional back taxes, he would pay them.
Mr Clinton denied he had interfered with federal investigations into various
aspects of Whitewater. He specifically refuted, though without anger,
allegations by respected Congressman Jim Leach, the Iowa Republican, of
interference with an investigation by the Kansas City branch of the
Resolution Trust Corporation, the savings and loan clean-up agency, into Mr
MacDougal's bank.
Mr Clinton staunchly defended his wife, Hillary, whose 'moral authority'
would emerge from Whitewater 'stronger than it has ever been'. He said she
had never earned income as a lawyer in Arkansas from state business while he
was governor.
Indeed, he showed no animus to anyone. He merely reflected that he had
learnt that 'there is a level of suspicion (in Washington) greater than I've
been accustomed to in the past'.
</TEXT>
