<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Observer: Kopper's cop-out?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
When the mighty Deutsche Bank first invited bank analysts for a debriefing
after its results a couple of years ago, the Anglo-Saxon scribblers marked
the event with a barrage of tricky questions. Their more biddable German
colleagues merely proposed a vote of thanks.
Deutsche executives readily admit they do not fully comprehend what
international investors expect of them in terms of information disclosure.
Hence great excitement at the promise, months ago, that this year's briefing
would be handled by Hilmar Kopper, Deutsche Bank's boss, and not an investor
relations flunky. Might Kopper lift the veil just a little bit on those
impenetrable accounts?
Imagine the let-down when faxes arrived explaining that 'unforeseen
circumstances' would prevent Kopper from turning up. 'As far as I can
ascertain, that consists of a board discussion and a credit meeting,'
scoffed one crest-fallen analyst. Clearly the Germans still think one buys
Deutsche Bank shares because they are there.
</TEXT>
