<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC1 is claiming that Tomorrow's World will undertake 'the biggest
experiment in the world' (7.30). As part of British Science Week viewers
will be asked to participate via telephone in deciding whether people tell
lies more convincingly on camera than on radio or in print. Is there any
conceivable value in this beyond a ratings-winning gimmick? The programme
makers seem chiefly preoccupied with providing sufficient telephone lines.
Perhaps it was just that Friday night feeling, but last week's opening
episode in ITV's new comedy, Time After Time, had me rolling around the old
green sofa in mirth. There is nothing 'alternative' or even very original
here. Car thief Kenny has come out of jail determined to go straight, but
his criminal family and friends either refuse to believe him or, like his
mother, feel deeply ashamed at this rejection of ancient family traditions
(8.30).
Geldof Goes Goondiwindi is a documentary record of the final concert played
by Bob Geldof on his Australian tour last summer (11.05 C4).
