<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Export order books strong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK manufacturers' export order books are close to their best level for
almost four years, but low total orders point to weakening domestic demand,
the Confederation of British Industry says in its March survey of industrial
trends today.
But manufacturers expect output to maintain a firmly upward trend over the
next four months and inflationary pressures to remain subdued. The survey
says export order books have improved over the last month. With 22 per cent
of manufacturers saying that export order books are above normal and 28 per
cent describing them as below normal, the negative balance of 6 per cent is
close to the best recorded since June 1990.
Total order books are described as above normal by 17 per cent of companies
and below normal by 30 per cent, a negative balance of 13 per cent, a slight
deterioration since last month - suggesting that domestic demand for UK
manufactured goods may be slackening ahead of April's tax increases.
But the CBI says the trend has improved markedly since March last year, when
there was a negative balance of 27 per cent. Together with February's
balance, overall demand is at its best level since December 1989.
</TEXT>
