FT  25 MAR 94 / Wage cost inflation subdued at 0.7%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The rate of growth of productivity slowed in the fourth quarter of last year
and the rise in unit wage costs remained subdued, the Department of
Employment said yesterday.
Productivity in the whole of the economy increased by 2.2 per cent in the
final three months of 1993 compared with a year earlier, down from 3 per
cent in the third quarter.
Unit wage costs rose 0.7 per cent in the fourth quarter compared with a year
earlier - unchanged from the previous quarter.
Mr Darren Winder, UK economist at SG Warburg Securities, said: 'It is quite
normal for productivity to be slowing two years into the recovery. We are
not going to see a second productivity miracle economy, although growth in
manufacturing output will boost productivity.'
Mr Kevin Gardiner, UK economist at Morgan Stanley, said: 'The economy is
experiencing a potent cyclical boost to productivity as employment bottoms
out and output rises.'
