<HEADLINE>
FT  25 MAR 94 / Euston main line upgrade studied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Pounds 500m modernisation of British Rail's west coast main line moved a
stage closer yesterday with the announcement of the award of a Pounds 3m to
Pounds 4m feasibility study to a consortium of four companies.
Railtrack, which will run BR's track and signalling, said the seven-year
project to upgrade the 480-mile link between London and Glasgow would set
the pattern for the private-sector management and financing of large
contracts. It would also be an important test of Railtrack's ability to
manage a project of this scale.
The nine-month study will be carried out by West Coast Main Line
Development, comprising Brown and Root, a project management company; Sir
Alexander Gibbs, a civil engineering consultancy; Booz Allen &amp; Hamilton, an
international consultancy; and Babcock and Brown, a specialist in transport
finance.
The consortium will consider how to improve the track, power supply and
signalling and how to raise private finance in a way which is acceptable to
the Treasury. It will also prepare tender documents to select a contracting
consortium in 1995.
The west coast line was the first BR main line to be electrified in the mid
1960s.
People, Page 14
</TEXT>
